subsection.p:
The column-oriented interpretation above is the foundation for our first algebraic operation with matrices. If \bA is an n\times n matrix and \bx is an n\times 1 vector, then we define 

    \bA\bx = x_1 \begin{bmatrix} a_{11}\\a_{21}\\\vdots\\a_{n1} \end{bmatrix} 
    + x_2 \begin{bmatrix} a_{12}\\a_{22}\\\vdots\\a_{n2} \end{bmatrix} 
    + \cdots + x_n \begin{bmatrix} a_{1n}\\a_{2n}\\\vdots\\a_{nn} \end{bmatrix} 
. 
That is, a matrix times a vector is a linear combination of the columns of the matrix.

example.p:
We can compute

    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ 2 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 4 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
    \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} 
    = 2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + 1 \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
    - 2 \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
    = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \\ 0 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
. 
Usually this sort of computation is not written out as a linear combination. Instead you just kind of zip together each row of \bA with the given vector:

    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\ 2 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 4 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
    \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} 
    = \begin{bmatrix} (1)(2) + (0)(1) + (-3)(-2) \\ (2)(2) + (-2)(1) + (1)(-2) \\ (0)(2) + (4)(1) + (1)(-2) \end{bmatrix}
.

program.input:
A = [ 1 2; -2 -4 ]; b = [1 ; 1];
clf fimplicit(@(x,y) A(1,1)*x+A(1,2)*y-b(1),[-2 2]) hold on fimplicit(@(x,y) A(2,1)*x+A(2,2)*y-b(2),[-2 2])
axis equal, grid on axis([-2 2 -2 2]) plot([0 0],[-2 2],'k-','linewid',2) plot([-2 2],[0 0],'k-','linewid',2) xlabel('x'), ylabel('y')

subsection.p:
The key to making the elimination work was the zero we forced into the second row of matrix representing the second system:

    \begin{bmatrix} 
    -1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 10
    \end{bmatrix}
. 
This matrix has what we call and upper triangular structure. That structure is our goal, because then we can sort of unzip the solution by starting at the bottom and working our way up.

In order to define the product \bA\bB, we require that the number of columns in \bA is the same as the number of rows in \bB. Otherwise, the product is considered undefined. So let \bA be m\times n and \bB be n\times p.  One way to describe  \bA\bB is as a  generalization of the matrix-vector product:

    \bA\mathbf{B} =
        \bA \begin{bmatrix}
        \mathbf{b}_1 \amp \mathbf{b}_2 \amp \cdots \amp \mathbf{b}_p
        \end{bmatrix}
        = \begin{bmatrix}
        \bA\mathbf{b}_1 \amp \bA\mathbf{b}_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bA\mathbf{b}_p
        \end{bmatrix}
.
In words, a matrix-matrix product is the horizontal concatenation of matrix-vector products involving the columns of the right-hand matrix. Note that when we multiply m\times n by n\times p, the result is m\times p.

example.p:
Let

    \bA = \begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 1
        \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
        \mathbf{B} = \begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2
        \end{bmatrix}
.  
Then 

    \bA\mathbf{B} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 
        (1)(2) + (-1)(1) \amp (1)(-1) + (-1)(1) \amp (1)(0) + (-1)(3) \amp (1)(4) + (-1)(2) \\
        (0)(2) + (2)(1) \amp (0)(-1) + (2)(1) \amp (0)(0) + (2)(3) \amp (0)(4) + (2)(2) \\
        (-3)(2) + (1)(1) \amp (-3)(-1) + (1)(1) \amp (-3)(0) + (1)(3) \amp (-3)(4) + (1)(2)
        \end{bmatrix} 
    \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
                1 \amp -2 \amp -3 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 6 \amp 4 \\ -5 \amp 4 \amp 3 \amp -10
            \end{bmatrix}
.

Observe that 

     \bA \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = 2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -3
         \end{bmatrix} + 1 \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
         = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}
 , 
 and so on.

subsection.p:
Even though a 2x2 inverse is easy, it's still not the most convenient way to solve a linear system. There is an even faster equivalent shortcut known as Cramer's Rule:

    x_1 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{b_1}{A_{12}}{b_2}{A_{22}} }{ \det(\bA) }
    x_2 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{A_{11}}{b_1}{A_{21}}{b_2} }{ \det(\bA) }   
.

introduction.p:
Say \bA is n\times n, and that we write 

    \bA \bv_1 = \lambda_1 \bv_1, \;
    \bA \bv_2 = \lambda_2 \bv_2,\; \dots, \;
    \bA \bv_n = \lambda_n \bv_n
,
where \lambda_1,\lambda_2,\dots,\lambda_n are its eigenvalues. Through some linear algebra magic, we can express this collection of equations more succinctly: 


         \begin{bmatrix} 
            \bA \bv_1 \amp \bA \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bA \bv_n 
        \end{bmatrix} 
        \amp = 
        \begin{bmatrix} 
            \lambda_1\bv_1 \amp \lambda_2\bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \lambda_n\bv_n 
        \end{bmatrix}

    \bA \begin{bmatrix} \bv_1 \amp \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bv_n \end{bmatrix}            \amp = 
        \begin{bmatrix} \bv_1 \amp \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bv_n \end{bmatrix} 
        \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\
                     0 \amp \lambda_2 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\
                     \amp \amp \ddots \amp \\
                     0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp \lambda_n
        \end{bmatrix}
    \bA \bV \amp = \bV \bD            
, 
where \bD is a diagonal matrix.

example.p:
Let's find a diagonalization of 

    \mathbf{A} =  \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
. 
We found the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of this guy in the previous section. We got \lambda_1=3 with \bv_1 = \twovec{1}{2}, and \lambda_2=-1 with \bv_2 =\twovec{1}{-2}. So we paint by numbers to get

    \mathbf{D} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad \bV = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
. 
We "just" need to invert \bV; fortunately, we're only at 2\times 2, so this is a snap.

    \bV^{-1} = \frac{1}{-4} \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/2 \amp 1/4 \\ 1/2 \amp -1/4 \end{bmatrix}
.  
Hence

    \mathbf{A} = \bV \mathbf{D} \bV^{-1} = 
    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} 
    \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} 
    \begin{bmatrix} 1/2 \amp 1/4 \\ 1/2 \amp -1/4 \end{bmatrix}
.

subsection.p:
Suppose \mathbf{y}'=\mathbf{A} \mathbf{y}. Given a diagonalization of \bA, we compute

     \mathbf{y}'\amp =\mathbf{V} \mathbf{D} \mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y}
    \mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y}' \amp=\mathbf{D} \mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y}
    (\mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y})' \amp=\mathbf{D} (\mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y})
. 
This suggests a change of variable, \mathbf{u} = \mathbf{V}^{-1} \mathbf{y}. Then

    \mathbf{u}' = \mathbf{D} \mathbf{u} 
    = \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 u_1 \\ \lambda_2 u_2 \\ \vdots \\ \lambda_n u_n \end{bmatrix}
. 
In terms of the new variable, the ODE system is u_1'=\lambda_1 u_1,\, \dots,\, u_n'=\lambda_n u_n, which are completely decoupledthat is, they evolve independently.

example.p:
In an earlier section we found the eigenstuff for 

    \bA = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}

as \lambda_1=3, \bv_1 = \twovec{1}{2}, and \lambda_2=-1, \bv_2=\twovec{1}{-2}. This means the general solution of \by'=\bA\by is 

    \by(t) = c_1 e^{3t} \twovec{1}{2} + c_2 e^{-t} \twovec{1}{-2} 
    = \twovec{ c_1 e^{3t} + c_2 e^{-t}}{2c_1 e^{3t} - 2 c_2e^{-t}}
.

Let's look at the solution of 

    \mathbf{y}' = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 5 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix} \mathbf{y}
. 
The eigenvalues are 1\pm i, with eigenvectors \twovec{1}{2\mp i}. So one form of the general solution is 

    c_1 e^{t} e^{it} \twovec{1}{2-i} + c_2 e^{t} e^{-it} \twovec{1}{2+i}
. 
With some work, we could convert this to a purely real form. Or, suppose we also have the initial condition \by(0)=\twovec{1}{-2}. This gives 

    c_1 \twovec{1}{2-i} + c_2 \twovec{1}{2+i} \amp = \twovec{1}{-2}
    \twomat{1}{1}{2-i}{2+i} \twovec{c_1}{c_2} \amp = \twovec{1}{-2}
. 
Using Cramer's rule, we get 

    c_1 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{1}{1}{-2}{2+i} }{ \twodet{1}{1}{2-i}{2+i} } = \frac{4+i}{2i}=\frac{-1-4i}{2}
    c_2 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{1}{1}{2-i}{-2} }{ \twodet{1}{1}{2-i}{2+i} } = \frac{-4+i}{2i}=\frac{-1+4i}{2}            
.

subsection.p:
Based on our experiences to date, we try an ODE solution of the form 

    te^{\lambda t} \mathbf{w}

for an unknown \bw. We plug this into the ODE and get 

    (\lambda t e^{\lambda t} + e^{\lambda t}) \mathbf{w} = t e^{\lambda t} \mathbf{A} \mathbf{w}
. 
We don't have enough terms to balance both the t^0 and t^1 groups. A better guess is 

    te^{\lambda t} \mathbf{v} + e^{\lambda t} \mathbf{w}
. Then

    (\lambda t e^{\lambda t} + e^{\lambda t}) \mathbf{v} + \lambda e^{\lambda t} \mathbf{w} = t e^{\lambda t} \mathbf{A} \mathbf{v} + e^{\lambda t} \mathbf{A} \mathbf{w}
.
Grouping together like terms, we have

     t( \mathbf{A} \mathbf{v} - \lambda \mathbf{v} ) + (  \mathbf{A} \mathbf{w} - \lambda \mathbf{w} ) = \mathbf{v}.

The term multiplying t is zero, by the eigenvector property. So we need only requiire

    (  \mathbf{A} - \lambda \mathbf{I} )  \mathbf{w} = \mathbf{v} 
,
which can be interpreted as a definition of a generalized eigenvector \bw. Even though the matrix here is singular, a solution for \bw is always possible.

example.p:
It's routine to show that 

    \bA = \twomat{0}{1}{-1}{0} = \twomat{1}{1}{i}{-i} \twodiag{i}{-i} \frac{1}{2} \twomat{1}{-i}{1}{i}
. 
From here we find that 

    e^{t\bA} \amp = \twomat{1}{1}{i}{-i} \twodiag{e^{it}}{e^{-it}} \frac{1}{2} \twomat{1}{-i}{1}{i}
    \amp = \frac{1}{2} \twomat{e^{it}}{e^{-it}}{ie^{it}}{-ie^{-it}} \twomat{1}{-i}{1}{i} 
    \amp = \frac{1}{2} \twomat{2\cos(t)}{-i[2i\sin(t)]}{i[2i\sin(t)]}{2\cos(t)}
    \amp = \twomat{\cos(t)}{\sin(t)}{-\sin(t)}{\cos(t)}
. 
This matrix applies a rotation of an angle t about the origin to all vectors in the plane. Thus, the phase portrait consists of concentric circles and the origin is a center.
